title: For Sale/Trade:  Level IIIA kevlar body armor bulletproof vest with plate carrier
postcontent:
I have a new, unissued level IIIA kevlar vest with plate carriers.  This armor was produced by First Choice Armor Company between 2009 and 2011. It has been in warehouse storage.  There are no rips, tears, stains, marks, or holes that I am aware of.  

The outer plate carrier is a dark navy blue color with two rows of MOLLE on the front chest, four rows on the back panel, and two rows on the sides.  The carrier adjusts for height by adjusting the velcro shoulder straps.  The carrier adjusts for waist size with velcro on the side panels that land on a velcro panel on the front of the carrier.  Inside both front and back panels of the carrier is a compartment that will accept ESAPI plates up to size 10" X 12".  The plate pockets are secured with velcro.  There is an area of velcro on the back panel of the carrier that allows for attachment of an armored collar for neck protection. The rear of the carrier has an emergency drag handle.  There is also a small velcro area on the front panel for attachment of an armored throat protector.  The front panel has a short row of MOLLE at the bottom for attachment of a groin protector.  The width of the rear panel with attached sides is 39".  The width of the front panel is 20".  Will fit up to 50" chest.  Allow a few inches of overlap onto the front panel for secure attachment.

The kevlar insert panels are also new and unissued.  The front panel is slightly smaller than the real panel.  The front panel is 15" tall, 11" wide at the top, and 19" wide at the bottom.  The rear panel is 17" tall, 11" wide at the top, and 19" wide at the bottom.  They are rated NIJ level IIIA.  They consist of 50 layers of Honeywell Goldflex inside a waterproof nylon shell.  Honeywell Goldflex is ounce for ounce stronger than Kevlar and thinner as well.  There are no ratings or identification tags of the armor panels themselves.

I also have several brand new MICH Kevlar combat helmets rated IIIA, as well as groin armor for these vests.

title: For Sale:  A very early postwar Smith and Wesson .38 Military & Police revolver
location: South St. Louis, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Smith and Wesson .38 Military & Police revolver for sale $490.00 or best offer. This is a very early postwar Smith and Wesson .38 Military & Police revolver. The S is actually part of the serial number. The S prefix guns were all made before the spring of 1948. This one dates back from late 1947 or early 1948. Only a factory letter can tell you exactly when it shipped, and it could be later, because S&W never shipped in serial number order. Sometimes revolvers sat in the vault for months or even years before they shipped. 
The stocks on this revolver are also period. This style only shipped for a few years right after the war. Later stocks looked a lot like this, but had a more rounded shoulder. If you take them off, you will probably find the serial number of this gun stamped into the wood of the right panel on the inside. That is the one location that will not include the S prefix.
This revolver is in very nice condition. The only wear/damage I see is on the bottom of the right stock panel. 
It is not really a collectible. For a gun in this era to fit that criterion, it would need to be As-new-in-box. However, it is a particularly nice revolver and some collectors might have an interest in it. 
If interested call Kovy at REDACTED
